“None of us was around to taste the famous twin vintages of 1928 and 1929 as young wines, but assessing the ‘85s and ‘86s may offer a comparable experience. STRATEGY FOR BUYING ’85s & ’86s:

Wise Bordeaux collectors are aware that the charming, delightful ’85s will reach their maturity well before the slow developing, classically great 1986 vintage. There- fore, many of our clientele have devoted a portion of their cellar to the 1985s which can be consumed soon after bottling. However, the ’86s are another story. They are truly big, enormous wines, rich in tannin, and are sure bets for the long haul—ideal wines to start drinking in 1992 and that will continue to blossom well into the next century. In effect, one should not ignore either year, but rather buy them in tandem to create a well-balanced collection of exceptional clarets.
